[1] Pakistan (Peshawar): wild birds, suspected
Date: Tue, 28 Mar 2006
From: Deborah MacKenzie <d.mackenzie@chello.be>
Source: Dailytimes, Pakistan, 27 Mar 2006 [edited]
<http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2006%5C03%5C27%5Cstory_27-3-2006_pg7_17>

Residents of the provincial capital and the areas adjacent to it have been
scared by reports of bird flu after hundreds of crows and kites (cheel)
have mysteriously died in the area in the 3 days following confirmation of
bird flu in 2 NWFP [North West Frontier Province] districts.
Reports of dead crows and kites, confirmed by locals and livestock disease
investigation officials, had been coming in from Shahi Bagh, Charsadda
Road, Gulf Course Avenue, University Camp and Palosai.
The medical community also expressed apprehensions about the birds' deaths.
Prof Dr Farmanullah of the Agriculture University, Peshawar confirmed the
deaths of 4 crows in his house. Similarly, Dr Munir of Peshawar University
also confirmed death of crows inside and outside his house. "I was not very
scared by the deaths of the crows in my house, but it was the number of
dead birds I saw outside my house that unsettled me," he said, adding that
the unusual and sudden deaths of these birds could well be attributed to
the deadly bird flu virus. Reports of unusual bird deaths have also been
confirmed in the Bajaur Agency, where several domesticated chickens and
wild birds have died since bird flu was confirmed in Charsadda and Abbottabad.
Dr Shir Mohammad, disease investigation officer at the NWFP Veterinary
Research Institute, Peshawar, has also confirmed unusual deaths of crows
and kites. "After receiving these reports, I dispatched my team to these
areas to collect blood samples from the dead birds immediately," he said.
Dr Shir Mohammad said that the team collected blood samples from the birds,
which were sent to the National Veterinary Research Laboratory in
Islamabad, for testing. He said, however, that these birds usually died at
this time of year. But this year, he said, the deaths of these birds had
proved more alarming, since the presence of the bird flu virus had been
confirmed in nearby Charsadda district. "We cannot be sure until we receive
the blood test results," he concluded.
[byline: Akhtar Amin]
--
Debora MacKenzie
Brussels correspondent
New Scientist
<d.mackenzie@chello.be>
[Pakistan's first cases of H5 in chickens, detected in the country's North
West Frontier Province, were reported to the OIE on 3 Mar 2006
<http://www.oie.int/eng/info/hebdo/AIS_28.HTM#Sec3>. They were later
confirmed by lab tests as H5N1 (see 20060321.0875). Peshawar, in Pakistan's
north west, faces the Afghan frontier: map at
<http://www.supertravelnet.com/maps/index.php?action=showmap&country=231_0_4&language=1>.
Information on the background of the mortality in wild birds, described in
the above newswire, would be appreciated. - Mod.AS]
