[2] Czech Republic, swan: first case, H5
Date: Tue, 28 Mar 2006
From: Mary Marshall <tropical.forestry@btinternet.com>
Source: AFP via Yahoo.com, 27 Mar 2006 [edited]
<http://news.yahoo.com/s/afp/20060327/hl_afp/healthfluczech_060327134419;_ylt=An9izmFvumn7SlngRuDpxbSTvyIi;_ylu=X3oDMTBiMW04NW9mBHNlYwMlJVRPUCUl>

The first case of bird flu in its H5 form has been detected in a dead swan
in the Czech Republic, and officials suspect that it could be the dangerous
H5N1 strain of the virus. "We have a serious suspicion of the presence of
H5N1, which will either be confirmed or not," minister of agriculture Jan
Mladek told a news conference. "We want the information to be as precise as
possible. We do not want to hide anything. Bird flu is dangerous but there
is no reason to panic," he added.
The virus was discovered in a dead swan at Hlubokou Nad Vltava in the south
of the country around 150 km (95 miles) south of Prague on 20 Mar 2006.
Further tests will be carried out in the Czech Republic and samples are to
be sent to the European Union laboratories in Britain, the head of the
state veterinary service, Milan Malena, told AFP after the news conference.
If the potentially deadly H5N1 strain of bird flu is confirmed, special
measures will be taken, including the creation of 3 and 10 km security
zones around the place where the dead swan was found. "We must learn to
live with this disease in the same way that we learned to live with mad cow
disease," Mladek added.
While all its neighbours -- Austria, Slovakia, Germany and Poland -- have
announced cases of bird flu, the Czech Republic has so far stood out as the
sole exception in Central Europe. Nevertheless, preparations to deal with
contamination have already been in place for several weeks.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Hluboka nad Vltavou (Latitude 49.0500, Longitude 14.4333, map at
<http://www.fallingrain.com/world/EZ/0/Hluboka_nad_Vltavou.html>) is a town
in the South Bohemia region, on the Vltava (Moldau) River. Final
identification of the isolate is anticipated. - Mod.AS]
