[3] Indonesia (Papua): suspected
Date: Tue, 28 Mar 2006
From: David Duffy <dduffy@hawaii.edu> and Ian Carter
<Ian.Carter@SESIAHS.HEALTH.NSW.GOV.AU>
Source: Papua New Guinea Post-Courier, 23 Mar 2006 [edited]
<http://www.postcourier.com.pg/> via Pacific Public Health Surveillance
Network <pacnet@lyris.spc.int>

Bird flu has been identified in the Indonesian province of Papua, which
shares the same land mass with Papua New Guinea.
National Agriculture Quarantine Inspection Authority officer in Kiunga
Kaiki Namalu said the disease has been positively identified at Timika, the
town that services the controversial Freeport Copper mine. [Timika is in
south central Papua Province, Indonesia; map at
<http://www.fallingrain.com/world/ID/0/Timuka.html>; Kiunga is a Papua New
Guinea town near the central border; map at
<http://www.fallingrain.com/world/PP/6/Kiunga.html> and at the PNG map
<http://www.sitesatlas.com/Maps/Maps/png-pol.htm>]
Mr Namalu said the National Agriculture Quarantine Inspection Authority has
placed a ban on the movement of birds and poultry to and from the West
Sepik and Western provinces. He said many people living in Kiunga and
Tabubil liked to take cassowary chicks [any of several large flightless
birds of the genus _Casuarius_ of Australia, New Guinea, and adjacent
areas, having a large bony projection on the top of the head and brightly
colored wattles] and guria pigeons [crested or crowned pigeons, _Goura
victoria_; see picture at
<http://www.bristolzoo.org.uk/learning/animals/birds/crowned-pigeon>] from
the 2 towns back to their home provinces when they go on holiday breaks.
But he cautioned people should not panic, despite the coverage that the
disease had been receiving in the international media.
Instead, Namalu said all people in the 2 border provinces had to be extra
vigilant, and if they see birds they suspect of having the disease, they
should report to the nearest Department of Primary Industry office or the
National Agriculture Quarantine Inspection Authority office. He also said
healthy live chickens could still bought from the markets and there was
nothing wrong with frozen chickens purchased from stores and supermarkets.
Namalu said the symptoms in birds were the same as in humans -- infected
birds will be seen sneezing, the comb on the head of male chickens drooping
and not erect as on healthy roosters. The infected birds will also look
drowsy and lack energy.
--
David Duffy, PCSU
Botany, University of Hawaii
Manoa, Hawaii, USA
<dduffy@hawaii.edu>
and
Ian Carter
Senior Hospital Scientist
Microbiology Department
St George Hospital
Gray St Kogarah 2217
New South Wales, Australia
<carteri@sesahs.nsw.gov.au>.
[Though still in need of verification, the news on suspected
south-eastwards spread of H5N1 into the Indonesian province of Papua is
cause for concern in the regional context. Further information, in
particular the results of laboratory investigation, would help. - Mod.AS]
